>Namaste friends,
>=A0
>There was=
 a discussion on Lord Vishnu's Dasavataras on a limited access forum on Fac=
ebook. A learned friend wrote that "Krshna is the God-man", "Previous Avata=
rs are a build-up to this stage" and "Buddha after Krshna is like going bac=
k from the linear progression of spirituality that the Avatars manifest one=
 after the other upto Krshna".
>=A0
>I want to emphatically disagree with t=
his notion that Dasavatars of a "linear progression of spirituality..upto K=
rshna".
>=A0
>*=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
>=A0
>Each av=
atara represents an aspect of Supreme in a perfected form.
>=A0
>Maharshi P=
arasara equated dasavataras with planets. For example, Rama, Krishna and Na=
rasimha are Sun, Moon and Mars, respectively.
>=A0
>We also
 know that Sun,=
 Moon, Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn, Rahu and Ketu are personifica=
tions of soul, mind, energy/initiative/drive, learning spirit, wisdom/discr=
imination, spirit of enjoyment/being happy, patience/discipline, spirit of =
innovation/breaking barriers and detachment (respectively).
>=A0
>Correspon=
dingly, each avatara is an expression of that aspect of Supreme in a perfec=
ted form. Each story is an example of how that aspect operates.
>=A0
>Lord =
Rama's story is a perfected example of how soul operates. Lord Krishna's st=
ory is a perfected example of how mind operates. Lord Vamana's story is a p=
erfected example of how wisdom/discrimination operates. Lord Narasimha's st=
ory is a perfected example of how energy/drive/initiative operates.
>=A0
>*=
=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
>=A0
>Now, let us remember o=
ne basic thing. Soul in us, mind in us, energy in us,
 learning spirit in u=
s, wisdom in us, happiness in us, discipline/patience in us - all these are=
 different manifestations of the same Self. However, when Self manifests as=
 these different aspects, it has different qualities and plays different ro=
les. There is no comparison between them.
>=A0
>We MAY focus on one aspect =
of us first, perfect it and then perfect other aspects through it. But, we =
need balance between all aspects in the end. Similarly, these different asp=
ects of Supreme Being are incomparable and are in a balance working togethe=
r in the Cosmos.
>=A0
>*=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
>=A0=

>One who is fascinated by the qualities of soul may like the story that de=
monstrates how soul operates; one who is fascinated by the qualities of min=
d may like the story that demonstrates how mind operates, and one who is fa=
scinated by the qualities of wisdom may like the story that
 demonstrates h=
ow wisdom operates. And so on. But this is just a matter of taste and subje=
ctive preference.
>=A0
>*=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
>=
=A0
>Let us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. Soul is seen as =
a representative of god in us, because of some basic attributes of it. It i=
s the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes.
>=A0
>Once mind=
 fancies a separate existence with some agendas/desires, soul supports the =
individualized consciousness stemming from that fancy and sees it as its dh=
arma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect of this individualized =
consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning ability, enjoyment, d=
iscipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no desires/agendas/likes=
/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and records all of one's =
agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper fruits later
 on. It =
does all that despite full awareness that it is neither doing those karmas =
nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects of the individualized c=
onsciousness entertain the notion that they are doing things and begetting =
the fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It sees that as its dhar=
ma and does it impassionately.
>=A0
>Now, does this sound exciting? Perhaps=
 not to all. This functionality of an impassionate witness supporting the p=
lay, may not seem interesting enough to some.
>=A0
>On the other hand, mind=
 has likes, dislikes and agendas. It is constantly pursuing those agendas, =
getting things and achieving things. Movement of mind is what keeps the ind=
ividualization going!!! Though soul is the support for everything else in t=
he individualized consciousness, soul is a witness doing its dharma impassi=
onately. It is mind that keeps the individualization going and brings in ag=
endas and passion and even decides/affects
 every entity's dharma. That way=
, mind is really the "boss" of the individualization. No wonder Krishna's l=
ife appeals more to one who may be excited by this description!
>=A0
>*=A0=
=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
>=A0
>Lord Krishna is obviously=
 awe-inspiring, but let me put Rama's life in perspective.
>=A0
>Rama's lif=
e demonstrates how soul operates. At a young age, he received Brahma Jnana =
from Vasishtha and became realized. Yet, he did whatever was his "dharma". =
He helped Vishwamitra. Soon after marriage, he was given kingdom. At the la=
st moment, his father banished him to forest at the behest of his step-moth=
er and his step-brother was given the throne. He had no complaints. Though =
his father, step-mother and step-brother felt guilty to various degrees, he=
 himself supported and consoled all three and followed his dharma impassion=
ately. Though he knew leaving Sita in the forest
 with Lakshmana and going =
after the golden deer would cause problems, he did it impassionately when S=
ita insisted. When she was kidnapped by Ravana, he searched for her and fou=
ght the battle. He never faulted Sita for forcing him to leave her or fault=
ed Lakshmana for leaving her later. He accepted every life situation with n=
o complaints and did the best possible action then. Even as he killed Ravan=
a, he did so without hatred or anger, but as his impassionate dharma. Even =
as Ravana was dying, he went to him and respectfully learned some subjects =
that were going to disappear with Ravana!
>=A0
>Rama is a perfect example o=
f a liberated man with no desires or agendas who impassionately discharges =
one's dharma arising from the momentum of karmas before liberation. THAT is=
 basically what soul does!
>=A0
>*=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=
=A0 *
>=A0
>As another example, let us look at Lord
 Vaamana. His story is =
a perfect demonstration of how wisdom/discrimination operates.
>=A0
>He was=
 born as a learned pygmy. He filled the entire cosmos to rid earth of a cha=
ritable demon king with many great qualities.
>=A0
>Wisdom/discrimination m=
akes one humble and unassuming. When one is doing good work but tainted wit=
h demonic qualities (e.g. pride or attachment), one's discrimination is not=
 pleased until that pride is suppressed. When wisdom fills one's entire con=
sciousness, then demonic qualities are completely suppressed.
>=A0
>*=A0=A0=
=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *
>=A0
>Please think about the other=
 avataras. The stories can be understood as perfect demonstrations of how v=
arious aspects of our consciousness operate, based on clues from Maharshi P=
arasara.
>=A0
>Let us not compare Dasavataras, but celebrate each of them s=
eparately. Of course, if you are more
 attracted to one of them, please thi=
nk about that avatara more and develop devotion. They are ALL capable of re=
lieving us from samsara.
>=A0
>*=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=
=A0 *
>=A0
>By the way, happy Hanumajjayanti to those who celebrate it toda=
y (there are different schools of thought).
>=A0
>Best regards,
>Narasimha
