bsp; *<br> <br>Let us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. S=
oul is seen as a representative of god in us, because of some basic attribu=
tes of it. It is the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes.<=
br> <br>Once mind fancies a separate existence with some agendas/desir=
es, soul supports the individualized consciousness stemming from that fancy=
 and sees it as its dharma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect o=
f this individualized consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning=
 ability, enjoyment, discipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no=
 desires/agendas/likes/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and=
 records all of one's agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper=
 fruits later
 on. It does all that despite full awareness that it is neith=
er doing those karmas nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects o=
f the individualized consciousness entertain the notion that they are doing=
 things and begetting the fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It=
 sees that as its dharma and does it impassionately.<br> <br>Now, does=
 this sound exciting? Perhaps not to all. This functionality of an impassio=
nate witness supporting the play, may not seem interesting enough to some.<=
br> <br>On the other hand, mind has likes, dislikes and agendas. It is=
 constantly pursuing those agendas, getting things and achieving things. Mo=
vement of mind is what keeps the individualization going!!! Though soul is =
the support for everything else in the individualized consciousness, soul i=
s a witness doing its dharma impassionately. It is mind that keeps the indi=
vidualization going and brings in agendas and passion and even decides/affe=
cts
 every entity's dharma. That way, mind is really the "boss" of the indi=
vidualization. No wonder Krishna's life appeals more to one who may be exci=
ted by this description!<br> <br>*      =
  *        *<br> <br>Lord Kris=
hna is obviously awe-inspiring, but let me put Rama's life in perspective.<=
br> <br>Rama's life demonstrates how soul operates. At a young age, he=
 received Brahma Jnana from Vasishtha and became realized. Yet, he did what=
ever was his "dharma". He helped Vishwamitra. Soon after marriage, he was g=
iven kingdom. At the last moment, his father banished him to forest at the =
behest of his step-mother and his step-brother was given the throne. He had=
